      "id": "file:///F:/hkicpa%20LP+Past%20paper/M1-10LP+Past%20paper/1-10%20Past%20paper/module1/Module%201%20Question%20Dec%202020.pdf#question-q-p005-1",
      "number": "1",
      "prompt": "Module 1 (December 2020 Session) Page 5 of 5 Question 4 (22 marks – approximately 39 minutes) Kim Limited engages in retail industry specialising in selling sportswear. Kim Limited received a bank statement issued by the World Bank on 5 June 2019 and found that the monthly balance as at 31 May 2019 did not agree with the company's bank account balance on the same date. In the cash book of Kim Limited, the bank account had a credit balance of HK$250. The accountant of the company found the following reasons for this: (1) The accounts clerk deposited cheques amounting to HK$15,000 into the World Bank through an auto teller machine after banking hours on 31 May 2019. The cheques were not processed by the bank until 3 June 2019. (2) On 4 June 2019, the World Bank informed Kim Limited that a cheque received from a customer for HK$33,000 was returned due to insufficient funds. The company had not yet recorded the return of this cheque in the cash book. (3) Cheque no.126877 for HK$5,200 and no.126878 for HK$12,300 had not yet been presented to the bank. (4) Bank service charges of HK$240 had not yet been recorded in the cash book. (5) A cheque drawn for HK$4,280 in payment of electricity had been entered in the cash book as HK$4,820. (6) A deposit of HK$2,000 had been entered in the credit side of the cash book. (7) It was found that a cheque drawn by Kan Limited in the amount of HK$5,000 had been recorded in Kim Limited's bank statement. (8) Debit side of the cash book had been undercast by HK$46,300. Required: (a) Prepare the bank column in the cash book of Kim Limited for May 2019. (8 marks) (b) Prepare a bank reconciliation statement for Kim Limited as at 31 May 2019. (8 marks) (c) Illustrate THREE examples of internal control over cash receipts in the retail stores of Kim Limited. (6 marks) * * * END OF EXAMINATION PAPER * * *",
      "full": "Module 1 (December 2020 Session) Page 5 of 5 Question 4 (22 marks – approximately 39 minutes) Kim Limited engages in retail industry specialising in selling sportswear. Kim Limited received a bank statement issued by the World Bank on 5 June 2019 and found that the monthly balance as at 31 May 2019 did not agree with the company's bank account balance on the same date. In the cash book of Kim Limited, the bank account had a credit balance of HK$250. The accountant of the company found the following reasons for this: (1) The accounts clerk deposited cheques amounting to HK$15,000 into the World Bank through an auto teller machine after banking hours on 31 May 2019. The cheques were not processed by the bank until 3 June 2019. (2) On 4 June 2019, the World Bank informed Kim Limited that a cheque received from a customer for HK$33,000 was returned due to insufficient funds. The company had not yet recorded the return of this cheque in the cash book. (3) Cheque no.126877 for HK$5,200 and no.126878 for HK$12,300 had not yet been presented to the bank. (4) Bank service charges of HK$240 had not yet been recorded in the cash book. (5) A cheque drawn for HK$4,280 in payment of electricity had been entered in the cash book as HK$4,820. (6) A deposit of HK$2,000 had been entered in the credit side of the cash book. (7) It was found that a cheque drawn by Kan Limited in the amount of HK$5,000 had been recorded in Kim Limited's bank statement. (8) Debit side of the cash book had been undercast by HK$46,300. Required: (a) Prepare the bank column in the cash book of Kim Limited for May 2019. (8 marks) (b) Prepare a bank reconciliation statement for Kim Limited as at 31 May 2019. (8 marks) (c) Illustrate THREE examples of internal control over cash receipts in the retail stores of Kim Limited. (6 marks) * * * END OF EXAMINATION PAPER * * *",
