      "number": "1",
      "prompt": "Module 10 (December 2023 Session) Page 3 of 6 Question 3 (15 marks – approximately 27 minutes) Eric is the sole shareholder and sole director of Good Wear Company Limited (\"GWL\"), which was set up in Hong Kong more than 20 years ago to operate a sports wear manufacturing business. Since his daughter Jenny graduated from university last year, Eric has allowed her to act as a director in GWL although she has never been formally appointed as a director. Jenny loves cars and has already bought two cars from a car dealer known as High Speed Company Limited (\"HSL\") in the name of GWL. These two cars have been duly paid for by GWL. Last week, Jenny placed an order for an expensive sports car with HSL again. Eric was shocked when he saw the invoice and refused to pay for the sports car. Eric told HSL that Jenny had never been appointed as a director of GWL and she had no authority to enter into contracts with any third parties. A few months ago, Eric began to consider selling the business of GWL because he wanted to retire. He wanted to know how much his business was worth and decided to engage an accounting firm, Reliable CPA & Co (\"RCC\"), to compile a business valuation report (the \"Report\") for his business, without mentioning his intention to sell his business. Tommy, the accountant who was assigned by RCC to compile the Report, negligently omitted to take into account a number of liabilities of GWL, which resulted in an over-valuation of GWL's business. Upon the completion of the Report, Eric passed the Report to Richard, an interested buyer who relied on the contents of the Report and subsequently bought Eric's business. Not long after having bought Eric's business, Richard realised that GWL's business was considerably overvalued and decided to seek legal advice on whether Richard could hold RCC liable for the misstatement in the Report. Required: (a) In relation to agency law, analyse whether GWL is liable to pay for the expensive sports car ordered by Jenny. (5 marks) (b) In relation to the tort of negligence, analyse whether Richard is entitled to hold RCC liable for negligent misstatement in the business valuation report. (10 marks)",
      "full": "Module 10 (December 2023 Session) Page 3 of 6 Question 3 (15 marks – approximately 27 minutes) Eric is the sole shareholder and sole director of Good Wear Company Limited (\"GWL\"), which was set up in Hong Kong more than 20 years ago to operate a sports wear manufacturing business. Since his daughter Jenny graduated from university last year, Eric has allowed her to act as a director in GWL although she has never been formally appointed as a director. Jenny loves cars and has already bought two cars from a car dealer known as High Speed Company Limited (\"HSL\") in the name of GWL. These two cars have been duly paid for by GWL. Last week, Jenny placed an order for an expensive sports car with HSL again. Eric was shocked when he saw the invoice and refused to pay for the sports car. Eric told HSL that Jenny had never been appointed as a director of GWL and she had no authority to enter into contracts with any third parties. A few months ago, Eric began to consider selling the business of GWL because he wanted to retire. He wanted to know how much his business was worth and decided to engage an accounting firm, Reliable CPA & Co (\"RCC\"), to compile a business valuation report (the \"Report\") for his business, without mentioning his intention to sell his business. Tommy, the accountant who was assigned by RCC to compile the Report, negligently omitted to take into account a number of liabilities of GWL, which resulted in an over-valuation of GWL's business. Upon the completion of the Report, Eric passed the Report to Richard, an interested buyer who relied on the contents of the Report and subsequently bought Eric's business. Not long after having bought Eric's business, Richard realised that GWL's business was considerably overvalued and decided to seek legal advice on whether Richard could hold RCC liable for the misstatement in the Report. Required: (a) In relation to agency law, analyse whether GWL is liable to pay for the expensive sports car ordered by Jenny. (5 marks) (b) In relation to the tort of negligence, analyse whether Richard is entitled to hold RCC liable for negligent misstatement in the business valuation report. (10 marks)",
      "options": [],
      "sourcePage": 3,
      "sourceMode": "text",
      "ocrUsed": false,
      "answer": "HK$1 billion for the most recent audited financial year.\nUnder Chapter 8A, each WVR beneficiary/ shareholder must:\n(ii) have an active executive role within the business and be a director at the time of listing.\nAs regards voting power, a WVR beneficiary must not be entitled to more than ten times the voting\npower of ordinary shares on any resolution tabled at the issuer's general meeting.\nNon-WVR shareholders must be entitled to cast at least 10% of the votes that are eligible to be cast\non resolutions at the listed issuer's general meetings.\nNon-WVR beneficiaries/ shareholders must be able to convene an extraordinary general meeting\nand add resolutions to the meeting agenda. The minimum stake required to do so must not be\nhigher than 10% of the voting rights on a one vote per share basis in the share capital of the listed\nissuer.\nChapter 8A also stipulates that the WVR beneficiaries must beneficially own collectively at least\n10% of the underlying economic interest in the applicant's total issued share capital at the time of\nits initial listing.\n* * * END OF EXAMINATION PAPER * * *\nModule 10 (December 2023 Session) Page 13 of 13\nCPA Certified Public Accountants\n~~ FEEHGAR",
