      "prompt": "(20 marks — approximately 36 minutes)\nAlvin and Kelvin are brothers and have been operating a successful restaurant business\nvia a limited company, Huge Profits Company Limited (\"HPL\"), since its incorporation\nfive years ago. HPL has adopted the Model Articles for Private Companies Limited\nby Shares as its Articles of Association.\nWhen HPL was set up, Alvin and Kelvin each subscribed 10,000 shares and were both\nappointed as directors of HPL. It was agreed that both Alvin and Kelvin would jointly run and\nmanage the restaurant business. Alvin was put in charge of the day-to-day operations, and\nKelvin was responsible for the corporate and investment strategies of the restaurant business.\nBoth Alvin and Kelvin have been drawing HK$80,000 a month as director's fees since\nthe incorporation of HPL.\nA year ago, Kelvin's son, Kenny, graduated from university and wished to take part\nin the restaurant business. Alvin agreed to appoint him as a director, and he even\ntransferred 5% of his shares in the Company to Kenny at the request of Kelvin because\nAlvin was childless and considered Kenny as his own son. It was agreed that Kenny\nwould be given HK$80,000 a month as director's fees as well.\nNot long after Kenny's appointment as a director of HPL, Kenny was given a substantial\nincrease in his director's fees despite Alvin's opposition. Subsequently, Alvin was removed\nfrom his directorship by an ordinary resolution in a general meeting despite his strong\nobjections. Kenny then took over the operation of the restaurant business and Alvin was\nkept in the dark as to what happened to HPL. Alvin was extremely upset.\nAlvin is now considering seeking legal advice on how to protect his rights as a minority\nshareholder.\nRequired:\nIn relation to company and winding-up laws of Hong Kong:\nremedies.\n(10 marks)\n(ii) Analyse whether Alvin is entitled to petition to the court for the winding-up\nof HPL.\n(10 marks)\nModule 10 (December 2023 Session) Page 5 of 6\nCPA hid pibiic Accountants\n-_ SERNGLR",
      "full": "Question 5 (20 marks — approximately 36 minutes)\nAlvin and Kelvin are brothers and have been operating a successful restaurant business\nvia a limited company, Huge Profits Company Limited (\"HPL\"), since its incorporation\nfive years ago. HPL has adopted the Model Articles for Private Companies Limited\nby Shares as its Articles of Association.\nWhen HPL was set up, Alvin and Kelvin each subscribed 10,000 shares and were both\nappointed as directors of HPL. It was agreed that both Alvin and Kelvin would jointly run and\nmanage the restaurant business. Alvin was put in charge of the day-to-day operations, and\nKelvin was responsible for the corporate and investment strategies of the restaurant business.\nBoth Alvin and Kelvin have been drawing HK$80,000 a month as director's fees since\nthe incorporation of HPL.\nA year ago, Kelvin's son, Kenny, graduated from university and wished to take part\nin the restaurant business. Alvin agreed to appoint him as a director, and he even\ntransferred 5% of his shares in the Company to Kenny at the request of Kelvin because\nAlvin was childless and considered Kenny as his own son. It was agreed that Kenny\nwould be given HK$80,000 a month as director's fees as well.\nNot long after Kenny's appointment as a director of HPL, Kenny was given a substantial\nincrease in his director's fees despite Alvin's opposition. Subsequently, Alvin was removed\nfrom his directorship by an ordinary resolution in a general meeting despite his strong\nobjections. Kenny then took over the operation of the restaurant business and Alvin was\nkept in the dark as to what happened to HPL. Alvin was extremely upset.\nAlvin is now considering seeking legal advice on how to protect his rights as a minority\nshareholder.\nRequired:\nIn relation to company and winding-up laws of Hong Kong:\n(a) Analyse whether Alvin is entitled to petition to the court for unfair prejudice\nremedies.\n(10 marks)\nb) (i) Explain to Alvin the grounds for winding up a company; and\n(ii) Analyse whether Alvin is entitled to petition to the court for the winding-up\nof HPL.\n(10 marks)\nModule 10 (December 2023 Session) Page 5 of 6\nCPA hid pibiic Accountants\n-_ SERNGLR",
