      "number": "1",
      "prompt": "Module 10 (December 2023 Session) Page 6 of 6 Question 6 (20 marks – approximately 36 minutes) Allan and Elsa have been actively involved in the design of innovative intelligent security systems for the protection of digital data since the incorporation of their company, Excellent Performance Company Limited (\"EPL\"), a few years ago. Allan and Elsa are the only shareholders and directors and have been doing extensive research and development in relation to their business. EPL owns valuable intellectual property rights and has experienced high growth in the last few years. Allan and Elsa wish to further expand their business and are thinking of getting the company listed on the Main Board of the Hong Kong Stock Exchange and offering shares of the company to the public. They are of the view that they need to continue to retain management control of EPL after the listing of EPL, should they be able to get EPL listed, because EPL owes much of its success to their expertise. Recently, Allan and Elsa have sought legal advice on the listing of EPL. They have been told that they would have to convert their private company into a public company. Furthermore, they have also been told that they may be able to retain control of the company after listing by means of the Weighted Voting Right (\"WVR\") Structure. Required: (a) In relation to company law of Hong Kong, explain to Allan and Elsa how to convert a private company into a public company. (10 marks) (b) In relation to the Listing Rules of the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, describe the Main Board listing requirements for the purpose of listing a company with a WVR Structure on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange. Note: You are not required to discuss company law. (10 marks) * * * END OF EXAMINATION PAPER * * *",
      "full": "Module 10 (December 2023 Session) Page 6 of 6 Question 6 (20 marks – approximately 36 minutes) Allan and Elsa have been actively involved in the design of innovative intelligent security systems for the protection of digital data since the incorporation of their company, Excellent Performance Company Limited (\"EPL\"), a few years ago. Allan and Elsa are the only shareholders and directors and have been doing extensive research and development in relation to their business. EPL owns valuable intellectual property rights and has experienced high growth in the last few years. Allan and Elsa wish to further expand their business and are thinking of getting the company listed on the Main Board of the Hong Kong Stock Exchange and offering shares of the company to the public. They are of the view that they need to continue to retain management control of EPL after the listing of EPL, should they be able to get EPL listed, because EPL owes much of its success to their expertise. Recently, Allan and Elsa have sought legal advice on the listing of EPL. They have been told that they would have to convert their private company into a public company. Furthermore, they have also been told that they may be able to retain control of the company after listing by means of the Weighted Voting Right (\"WVR\") Structure. Required: (a) In relation to company law of Hong Kong, explain to Allan and Elsa how to convert a private company into a public company. (10 marks) (b) In relation to the Listing Rules of the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, describe the Main Board listing requirements for the purpose of listing a company with a WVR Structure on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange. Note: You are not required to discuss company law. (10 marks) * * * END OF EXAMINATION PAPER * * *",
      "options": [],
      "sourcePage": 6,
      "sourceMode": "text",
      "ocrUsed": false,
      "answer": "HK$1 billion for the most recent audited financial year.\nUnder Chapter 8A, each WVR beneficiary/ shareholder must:\n(ii) have an active executive role within the business and be a director at the time of listing.\nAs regards voting power, a WVR beneficiary must not be entitled to more than ten times the voting\npower of ordinary shares on any resolution tabled at the issuer's general meeting.\nNon-WVR shareholders must be entitled to cast at least 10% of the votes that are eligible to be cast\non resolutions at the listed issuer's general meetings.\nNon-WVR beneficiaries/ shareholders must be able to convene an extraordinary general meeting\nand add resolutions to the meeting agenda. The minimum stake required to do so must not be\nhigher than 10% of the voting rights on a one vote per share basis in the share capital of the listed\nissuer.\nChapter 8A also stipulates that the WVR beneficiaries must beneficially own collectively at least\n10% of the underlying economic interest in the applicant's total issued share capital at the time of\nits initial listing.\n* * * END OF EXAMINATION PAPER * * *\nModule 10 (December 2023 Session) Page 13 of 13\nCPA Certified Public Accountants\n~~ FEEHGAR",
