      "number": "1",
      "prompt": "Module 10 (December 2024 Session) Page 3 of 7 Question 3 (25 marks – approximately 45 minutes) Matthew and Winnie are good friends. Matthew is employed by Global Trading Company Limited (\"GTL\") as a Sales Executive. Winnie is an IT expert and is dissatisfied with her income. A few months ago, Winnie got acquainted with a few other IT experts and they began to scam people out of their money by engaging in internet fraud. Instead of depositing her proceeds into her own bank account, Winnie requested Matthew to open a few bank accounts so that she could deposit various amounts into each of his bank accounts. Winnie would then ask Matthew to remit those amounts to her or to other third parties whom Matthew did not know. Winnie offered to pay Matthew a certain sum of money each time. Matthew did what she requested him to do without asking any questions as Matthew's wife had recently lost her job. A few weeks ago, Winnie called Matthew during office hours to tell him she needed money urgently. Winnie asked Matthew to pick her up and drive her to CDE Bank to withdraw money from one of Matthew's accounts into which she had deposited some money. Winnie offered to give Matthew double the amount she had promised to give him for doing this. As a Sales Executive, Matthew has been entrusted with the key to the company car so that he can drive to visit clients and suppliers. However, Matthew must obtain prior permission from the General Manager Peter before using the company car. Without obtaining permission from Peter, Matthew took the company car to pick Winnie up and drove her to CDE Bank to withdraw money out of his account and then gave the money to Winnie. In order to avoid any of his colleagues finding out that he had taken the company car without permission, Matthew tried to get back to his office as quickly as he could. As Matthew was driving very fast, he did not notice that the traffic light had turned red. Matthew drove through a red light and injured an elderly pedestrian Mrs Slow. Required: (a) In relation to anti-money laundering laws of Hong Kong, including common law and the Organized and Serious Crimes Ordinance (Cap.455), analyse whether Matthew might have committed any criminal offence by doing what Winnie has asked him to do. (5 marks) (b) In relation to the tort of negligence, explain the essential elements of negligence and analyse whether Mrs Slow can bring a claim against Matthew on the grounds of negligence. (10 marks) (c) In relation to employment law, analyse whether GTL can be held vicariously liable for Matthew's wrongful act if Mrs Slow decides to sue both Matthew and GTL for damages for her injury. (10 marks)",
