      "number": "1",
      "prompt": "Module 10 (December 2020 Session) Page 4 of 6 Required: In relation to tort of negligence: (a) Analyse whether Alan would be liable for negligent misstatement and whether Alan owes a duty of care to the Bank as an auditor. Note: You are not required to answer the statutory liability of auditors under the Companies Ordinance (Cap 622). (5 marks) (b) Analyse whether Alan would be liable if the Report were prepared with the knowledge that the Bank would rely on the Report in determining the loan. (5 marks) Question 5 (10 marks – approximately 18 minutes) Mother Ltd is a private company limited by shares, which is incorporated in Hong Kong with a HK$100,000,000 share capital. It is well established and known for Chinese food products. Son Ltd is a company incorporated in Hong Kong and wholly owned by Mother Ltd producing Korean food products under Mother Ltd's brand. Son Ltd is a private company limited by shares with a HK$10,000 share capital. The board of directors of Mother Ltd and Son Ltd are the same. Due to an error in the manufacturing process, the Korean food products of Son Ltd were infected with a bacteria. A customer bought the Korean food products of Son Ltd from a supermarket. The customer was diagnosed as suffering from acute abdominal pain and diarrhea as a result of eating the Korean food products of Son Ltd. A government laboratory later examined the Korean food products and determined that the products of Son Ltd contained a bacteria. There were many claims against Son Ltd. Son Ltd did not have sufficient resources to settle the claims and Mother Ltd refused to inject further capital into Son Ltd. Son Ltd became insolvent and went into liquidation. The customer would like to sue both Mother Ltd and Son Ltd for damages as he knew that the board of directors between Mother Ltd and Son Ltd are identical. Required: In relation to company law: (a) Explain the principles of separate legal entity and limited liability. (5 marks) (b) Analyse whether Mother Ltd would be liable for the liability of Son Ltd by referring to the principles under Question 5(a). (5 marks)",
