      "number": "1",
      "prompt": "Module 10 (June 2023 Session) Page 2 of 6 Question 2 (20 marks – approximately 36 minutes) Nancy has been running a dessert shop in a village in the New Territories as a sole proprietor for more than ten years. During that period, Nancy has been earning a stable decent income from her business. About six months ago, Nancy began to think of retiring and selling her business because her doctor advised her to relax and take good care of her health. Ronald expressed interest in buying Nancy's business and visited Nancy's dessert shop. During the visit, Ronald noticed that Nancy's business was good and asked Nancy whether there was any competitor in the neighbourhood. Nancy said that there was no other dessert shop in the village and told Ronald the approximate amount of income earned from her business in the last three years. Unknown to Nancy, about a year ago, a young lady called Eva moved into the village and decided to open a similar style dessert shop. As Eva was not a sociable person and did not try to make friends with other people in the village, Nancy and other people in the village did not really notice what she was doing. Relying on Nancy's representation that there would be no competitor in the neighbourhood and believing that he would also be able to earn a stable decent income like Nancy, Ronald decided to enter into a contract with Nancy to buy her business. On the day of signing of the contract, Nancy did not know that Eva's dessert shop was already in operation. Not long after Ronald had opened his dessert shop, Ronald noticed that there was another dessert shop in the village which was operated by Eva and business there was good. Ronald found that the income he earned from his business continued to decline. When asked by Ronald about the existence of Eva's dessert shop, Nancy replied that she knew nothing about it before or on the day of their signing of the contract. Ronald did not believe what Nancy said. Required: (a) In relation to contract law, analyse whether Ronald can bring a claim for misrepresentation against Nancy on the basis of what Nancy said about there being no competitor in the neighbourhood before Ronald entered into the contract with her to buy her business. (10 marks) (b) On the basis of your answer in part (a), analyse what remedies are available to Ronald, if any. (5 marks) (c) Analyse which court/ tribunal has jurisdiction to deal with Ronald's case if Ronald's claim involves an amount of more than HK$75,000 and up to HK$3 million. (5 marks)",
