      "number": "1",
      "prompt": "Module 10 (June 2023 Session) Page 4 of 6 Question 4 (15 marks – approximately 27 minutes) Roy runs a small transportation business as a sole proprietor. While Roy was driving his cargo van to deliver goods to a client a few months ago, he received a call from his daughter who told him she had received an offer from a university in Hong Kong. As Roy was overjoyed, he kept talking to his daughter and did not notice that the traffic light had turned red. Roy ran a red light and knocked down an elderly pedestrian, Mrs. Young, who was crossing the road. Mrs. Young was badly injured. After being hospitalised for several months, Mrs. Young recovered from her injury but was wheelchair-bound. Before Mrs. Young's discharge from hospital, her son Tom wanted to buy her a good wheelchair. Tom went to a shop called \"Good Equipment\" to buy a wheelchair for his mother. Tom selected a wheelchair and bought it after having briefly examined it. On the day when the wheelchair was delivered, Mrs. Young wanted to ride on it to go to the park, Tom accompanied Mrs. Young to the park. When Mrs. Young reached the park, she tried to stop the wheelchair but found that the brake did not work. Luckily, Tom managed to stop the wheelchair from hitting a tree. Mrs. Young was terrified. Required: In relation to tort of negligence and sales of goods law: (a) Analyse the essential elements of negligence and analyse whether Mrs. Young can bring a claim against Roy on the grounds of negligence. (10 marks) (b) Analyse whether the shop \"Good Equipment\" was in breach of any implied terms of the Sale of Goods Ordinance (Cap.26) (\"SOGO\") and analyse as to what rights Tom may have under the SOGO. (5 marks)",
