      "full": "Module 10 (June 2023 Session) Page 6 of 6 Question 6 (15 marks – approximately 27 minutes) Brilliant Company Limited (\"BCL\") is a private company limited by shares which imports clothes made of recycled materials from overseas manufacturers. Excellent Company Limited (\"ECL\") is also a private company limited by shares and it is wholly owned by BCL. ECL markets and sells products imported by BCL. Both BCL and ECL are incorporated in Hong Kong and the members of the Board of Directors of both BCL and ECL are the same. Both BCL and ECL carry out their own business properly and in accordance with the law. Recently, a customer called Helen made a complaint to ECL that she had contracted a skin disease after wearing an evening gown purchased from ECL. On recommendation from a doctor, Helen arranged for a laboratory testing of the materials of the evening gown. It was found that the materials of which the evening gown was made contained toxic substances which caused the skin disease suffered by Helen. Helen subsequently incurred substantial medical expenses for the treatment of her skin disease. Helen asked ECL to pay her compensation for the medical expenses she incurred. ECL did not have sufficient funds or assets to pay Helen the amount of compensation she requested. ECL asked BCL for financial assistance but BCL refused to give ECL any financial assistance. Knowing that ECL is wholly owned by BCL and the members of the Board of Directors of both BCL and ECL are the same, Helen wishes to sue both BCL and ECL for damages. Required: In relation to company law: (a) Explain the principles of separate legal entity and limited liability. (5 marks) (b) Given that ECL did not have funds to pay damages it would be liable to pay to Helen, analyse whether BCL would be liable to pay to Helen such damages by referring to the principles discussed in part (a). (You do NOT need to discuss contract law principles or tort law principles in your answer.) (10 marks) * * * END OF EXAMINATION PAPER * * *",
