      "number": "1",
      "prompt": "Module 10 (June 2024 Session) Page 4 of 6 Question 4 (20 marks – approximately 36 minutes) Timothy owns and operates a Hong Kong incorporated private limited company, Great Art Company Limited (\"GAL\"), which deals in expensive fine arts such as sculptures and paintings. Susanna is employed as the Executive Secretary of GAL. As Susanna has a bachelor's degree in fine arts, Timothy occasionally asks her to give him advice on the purchase of works of fine arts to be resold to clients. Timothy has, however, expressly told Susanna not to place orders for any artwork without obtaining his prior approval. About a week ago, Susanna saw a painting at the grand opening of an art gallery, Excellent Art Gallery (\"EAG\"), with a price tag of HK$200,000. Susanna thought it was a good bargain and placed an order for the painting without asking Timothy for approval. When the painting was delivered, Timothy was very pleased with what Susanna had done and asked her to take the painting to a wealthy client, Mr Rich, being confident that Mr Rich would be willing to buy it at HK$300,000. The next day, Susanna delivered the painting to the office of Mr Rich, who liked the painting very much and decided to buy it. He took the painting and promised to send a cheque to GAL in two weeks. After leaving Mr Rich's office, Susanna went to a café, Great Taste Café (\"GTC\"), to have breakfast. After having breakfast and while on her way back to her office in a taxi, Susanna suddenly felt great pain in her stomach and was taken to the closest hospital. Susanna was subsequently diagnosed to have suffered from food poisoning and it was found that other customers who visited GTC that day also suffered from food poisoning. Susanna had to stay at the hospital for ten days and incurred substantial medical costs. While Susanna was still in the hospital, Mr Rich returned the painting because he was experiencing financial difficulties due to the unexpected decline of his business. At the same time, EAG sent an invoice to GAL to ask for payment for the painting. Timothy thinks that Susanna did not have the authority to place an order for the painting and is now wondering whether GAL is liable to pay for it. Required: (a) In relation to agency law: (i) Explain the various ways of creation of agency. (4 marks) (ii) Analyse whether GAL is liable to pay for the painting delivered by EAG. (6 marks) (b) In relation to the tort of negligence, explain the essential elements of negligence and analyse whether Susanna is entitled to bring a claim against GTC. (10 marks)",
