      "answer": "Module 10 (June 2021 Session) Page 11 of 11 In this case, the shop can terminate the employment with Steven without notice having regard to his conduct under either the common law or legislation. Note: Unless otherwise stated, the references to the above provision(s) are made to the Employment Ordinance (Cap.57). Answer 7(d) The question required candidates to discuss the contractual, common law and fiduciary duties of an agent. The agent has a contractual duty to follow the principal's instructions and failure to do so will amount to a breach of agency under the law of contract. The agent must perform his/ her duties with accepted standard of skill and competence under the common law. Agency is a fiduciary relationship that imposes a strict obligation on the agent not to promote personal interests in preference to those of the principal. The agent should not put himself/ herself in a position where his/ her personal interests come ahead of, conflict or clash with that of the principal. The agent must not make a secret profit or acquire any benefit in the course of the agency without the principal's consent. The agent must account to the principal for all money he/ she receives on the principal's behalf and the agent must keep a proper record for all transactions. The agent is also liable to account for any profit that he/ she has made from transaction undisclosed to the principal. In this case, Steven is an employee and an agent duly authorised by the shop to buy dried seafood. Steven is in breach of the contract law, common law and fiduciary duties. As such, Steven is liable to pay damages to Maggie. * * * END OF EXAMINATION PAPER * * *\nIn this case, the shop can terminate the employment with Steven without notice having regard\nto his conduct under either the common law or legislation.\nNote: Unless otherwise stated, the references to the above provision(s) are made to\nthe Employment Ordinance (Cap.57).\nThe question required candidates to discuss the contractual, common law and fiduciary\nduties of an agent.\nThe agent has a contractual duty to follow the principal's instructions and failure to do so will\namount to a breach of agency under the law of contract.\nThe agent must perform his/ her duties with accepted standard of skill and competence under\nthe common law.\nAgency is a fiduciary relationship that imposes a strict obligation on the agent not to promote\npersonal interests in preference to those of the principal.\nThe agent should not put himself/ herself in a position where his/ her personal interests come\nahead of, conflict or clash with that of the principal.\nThe agent must not make a secret profit or acquire any benefit in the course of the agency\nwithout the principal's consent.\nThe agent must account to the principal for all money he/ she receives on the principal's\nbehalf and the agent must keep a proper record for all transactions. The agent is also liable\nto account for any profit that he/ she has made from transaction undisclosed to the principal.\nIn this case, Steven is an employee and an agent duly authorised by the shop to buy dried\nseafood. Steven is in breach of the contract law, common law and fiduciary duties.\nAs such, Steven is liable to pay damages to Maggie.\n* * * END OF EXAMINATION PAPER * * *",
