      "prompt": "(15 marks — approximately 27 minutes)\nYou are required to complete the following tasks in this question:\nIn relation to the contract law in Hong Kong:\nwas frustrated by the fire which had resulted in reduced pedestrian flows and\nreduced business. (5 marks)\nCase Background:\nAfter having worked as a chef at a hotel for a few years, Sam decided to open his own\nrestaurant. About a year ago, Sam entered into a tenancy agreement with Mrs Rich\npursuant to which Mrs Rich leased to Sam a shop in a mall at Causeway Bay. Due to the\nweak economy, Sam's restaurant business was not very good. One day, a fire accidentally\nbroke out and as a result the mall had to be closed for about two weeks. Sam's shop was\nnot badly damaged by the fire but he wishes to stop paying the rent and rates soon after the\nfire.\nSoon after the re-opening of the mall, Sam asked his landlord Mrs Rich for a 50% reduction\nin rent on the grounds of reduced pedestrian flows which made doing business very difficult.\nWhile Sam was having a chat with a friend who was a lawyer, he was advised that a contract\ncould be discharged by frustration. When Mrs Rich refused Sam's request, Sam stopped\npaying the rent and rates. Later Mrs Rich threatened to sue Sam for the outstanding rent\nand rates, Sam argued that the tenancy agreement he had entered into with Mrs Rich was\nfrustrated due to the temporary closure of the mall which in turn led to reduced pedestrian\nflows and therefore reduced business. Sam also alleged that there were structural defects\nin the mall without providing any proof for this allegation.\n+ + * ENDOFSCENARIO x * =x\nModule 10 (December 2025 Session) Page 2 of 6\nCPA hid pibiic Accountants\n-_ SERNGLR",
      "full": "Question 2 (15 marks — approximately 27 minutes)\nYou are required to complete the following tasks in this question:\nIn relation to the contract law in Hong Kong:\n(a) Explain the different ways to discharge a contract. (70 marks)\n(b) Analyse whether the tenancy agreement entered into between Sam and Mrs Rich\nwas frustrated by the fire which had resulted in reduced pedestrian flows and\nreduced business. (5 marks)\nCase Background:\nAfter having worked as a chef at a hotel for a few years, Sam decided to open his own\nrestaurant. About a year ago, Sam entered into a tenancy agreement with Mrs Rich\npursuant to which Mrs Rich leased to Sam a shop in a mall at Causeway Bay. Due to the\nweak economy, Sam's restaurant business was not very good. One day, a fire accidentally\nbroke out and as a result the mall had to be closed for about two weeks. Sam's shop was\nnot badly damaged by the fire but he wishes to stop paying the rent and rates soon after the\nfire.\nSoon after the re-opening of the mall, Sam asked his landlord Mrs Rich for a 50% reduction\nin rent on the grounds of reduced pedestrian flows which made doing business very difficult.\nWhile Sam was having a chat with a friend who was a lawyer, he was advised that a contract\ncould be discharged by frustration. When Mrs Rich refused Sam's request, Sam stopped\npaying the rent and rates. Later Mrs Rich threatened to sue Sam for the outstanding rent\nand rates, Sam argued that the tenancy agreement he had entered into with Mrs Rich was\nfrustrated due to the temporary closure of the mall which in turn led to reduced pedestrian\nflows and therefore reduced business. Sam also alleged that there were structural defects\nin the mall without providing any proof for this allegation.\n+ + * ENDOFSCENARIO x * =x\nModule 10 (December 2025 Session) Page 2 of 6\nCPA hid pibiic Accountants\n-_ SERNGLR",
