      "number": "1",
      "prompt": "Module 10 (December 2025 Session) Page 5 of 6 Question 5 (10 marks – approximately 18 minutes) You are required to complete the following tasks in this question: In relation to partnership law in Hong Kong: (a) Explain to Chloe what the duties and liabilities of partners of a general partnership are. (6 marks) (b) Analyse whether Mr Mean is entitled to choose to sue Peter only but not the other partners, Sylvia and John, for damages and whether Peter will be able to recover from Sylvia and John the amount of damages which he has to pay to Mr Mean on their behalf. (4 marks) Case Background: After graduating from her interior design studies with distinction at a local university a few months ago, Chloe was invited by Peter, a good friend of Chloe's cousin, to join as partner of a general partnership, Magnificent Design Studio (\"MDS\"), set up by Peter and two of his friends, Sylvia and John, a few years ago. Chloe is not sure whether to accept Peter's offer as Chloe has no idea of what the duties and liabilities of a partner of a general partnership are. Due to the negligence recently committed by Sylvia and John while working on a design project commissioned by a client Mr Mean, Mr Mean has sustained loss of HK$2 million and has asked MDS for compensation. However, MDS does not have funds or assets to pay this amount. Knowing that Peter comes from a rich family and has just inherited a huge amount of money from his grandfather, Mr Mean plans to commence legal proceedings only against Peter for damages of HK$2 million. ∗ ∗ ∗ END OF SCENARIO ∗ ∗ ∗",
      "full": "Module 10 (December 2025 Session) Page 5 of 6 Question 5 (10 marks – approximately 18 minutes) You are required to complete the following tasks in this question: In relation to partnership law in Hong Kong: (a) Explain to Chloe what the duties and liabilities of partners of a general partnership are. (6 marks) (b) Analyse whether Mr Mean is entitled to choose to sue Peter only but not the other partners, Sylvia and John, for damages and whether Peter will be able to recover from Sylvia and John the amount of damages which he has to pay to Mr Mean on their behalf. (4 marks) Case Background: After graduating from her interior design studies with distinction at a local university a few months ago, Chloe was invited by Peter, a good friend of Chloe's cousin, to join as partner of a general partnership, Magnificent Design Studio (\"MDS\"), set up by Peter and two of his friends, Sylvia and John, a few years ago. Chloe is not sure whether to accept Peter's offer as Chloe has no idea of what the duties and liabilities of a partner of a general partnership are. Due to the negligence recently committed by Sylvia and John while working on a design project commissioned by a client Mr Mean, Mr Mean has sustained loss of HK$2 million and has asked MDS for compensation. However, MDS does not have funds or assets to pay this amount. Knowing that Peter comes from a rich family and has just inherited a huge amount of money from his grandfather, Mr Mean plans to commence legal proceedings only against Peter for damages of HK$2 million. ∗ ∗ ∗ END OF SCENARIO ∗ ∗ ∗",
      "options": [],
      "sourcePage": 5,
      "sourceMode": "text",
      "ocrUsed": false,
      "answer": "Module 10 (December 2025 Session) Page 14 of 14 Based on the Yik Fong Fong case, it is likely that Sam and Nancy have committed the offence of insider dealing u nder s s.271(1)(e) and 291(5) as they had probably obtained inside information from Maggie and allowed the purchase and sale of the shares of HGL to be conducted through their accounts during the period of negotiations between HGL and HWL. Nancy's defence, namely that she did not care about what shares had been bought and sold through her securities account because she had to take care of her sick mother at the material times, will probably not be accepted by the Court if she is subsequently charged with insider dealing. Note: Unless otherwise stated, the references to the above provision(s) are made to the Securities and Futures Ordinance (Cap.571). * * * END OF EXAMINATION PAPER * * *\nBased on the Yik Fong Fong case, it is likely that Sam and Nancy have committed the offence of\ninsider dealing under ss.271(1)(e) and 291(5) as they had probably obtained inside information from\nMaggie and allowed the purchase and sale of the shares of HGL to be conducted through their\naccounts during the period of negotiations between HGL and HWL.\nNancy's defence, namely that she did not care about what shares had been bought and sold\nthrough her securities account because she had to take care of her sick mother at the material\ntimes, will probably not be accepted by the Court if she is subsequently charged with insider dealing.\nNote: Unless otherwise stated, the references to the above provision(s) are made to the Securities\nand Futures Ordinance (Cap.571).\n* * * ENDOF EXAMINATION PAPER * * *",
