      "kind": "Question",
      "sourceMatch": "Module 9 (December 2024 Session) Page 9 of 11 Question 3 (11 marks – approximately 20 minutes) P Limited (\"the Company\") is incorporated and carrying on business in Hong Kong. Joe ",
      "id": "file:///F:/hkicpa%20LP+Past%20paper/M1-10LP+Past%20paper/1-10%20Past%20paper/m9/M9%20Question%20Dec%202024.pdf#question-q-p009-1",
      "number": "1",
      "prompt": "Module 9 (December 2024 Session) Page 9 of 11 Question 3 (11 marks – approximately 20 minutes) P Limited (\"the Company\") is incorporated and carrying on business in Hong Kong. Joe is the Company's director. On 1 December 2022, the Company received a notice of estimated profits tax assessment for the year of assessment 2021/22 dated 29 November 2022. Joe told you that the Company was busily engaged in a new project and failed to file the 2021/22 profits tax return. He said that the Company did not earn the huge amount of profit estimated by the IRD. Assume today is 15 December 2022. Joe has approached you for advice and wonders whether the Company is required to pay tax as demanded if it has objected against the assessment. Required: (a) Describe the requirements of a valid objection against an assessment and the possible grounds for extension as provided under the IRO. (8 marks) (b) Analyse, with the relevant provisions of the IRO, whether the tax in dispute can be deferred until the settlement of the objection. (3 marks) Question 4 (9 marks – approximately 16 minutes) Mr Johnston sold a commercial property in Central (\"the Property\") to Mr Howard for a consideration of HK$20,000,000. The terms of payment are cash of HK$15,000,000 and 100,000 shares in XYZ Limited, which is a Hong Kong incorporated company. At the date of the agreement of sales and purchase effecting from the sale of the Property, 15 October 2022, the market value of XYZ Limited shares is HK$200 per share. Mr Johnston and Mr Howard are Hong Kong permanent residents. They are not related to each other. Mr Johnston acquired the Property back in 1996 from Mrs Hughes, a non-Hong Kong permanent resident. Required: With reference to the relevant provisions under the Stamp Duty Ordinance, analyse whether ad valorem stamp duty, special stamp duty and buyer's stamp duty are payable on the agreement for sale and purchase and the transfer of shares, respectively. If so, compute the respective amounts payable. (9 marks)",
      "full": "Module 9 (December 2024 Session) Page 9 of 11 Question 3 (11 marks – approximately 20 minutes) P Limited (\"the Company\") is incorporated and carrying on business in Hong Kong. Joe is the Company's director. On 1 December 2022, the Company received a notice of estimated profits tax assessment for the year of assessment 2021/22 dated 29 November 2022. Joe told you that the Company was busily engaged in a new project and failed to file the 2021/22 profits tax return. He said that the Company did not earn the huge amount of profit estimated by the IRD. Assume today is 15 December 2022. Joe has approached you for advice and wonders whether the Company is required to pay tax as demanded if it has objected against the assessment. Required: (a) Describe the requirements of a valid objection against an assessment and the possible grounds for extension as provided under the IRO. (8 marks) (b) Analyse, with the relevant provisions of the IRO, whether the tax in dispute can be deferred until the settlement of the objection. (3 marks) Question 4 (9 marks – approximately 16 minutes) Mr Johnston sold a commercial property in Central (\"the Property\") to Mr Howard for a consideration of HK$20,000,000. The terms of payment are cash of HK$15,000,000 and 100,000 shares in XYZ Limited, which is a Hong Kong incorporated company. At the date of the agreement of sales and purchase effecting from the sale of the Property, 15 October 2022, the market value of XYZ Limited shares is HK$200 per share. Mr Johnston and Mr Howard are Hong Kong permanent residents. They are not related to each other. Mr Johnston acquired the Property back in 1996 from Mrs Hughes, a non-Hong Kong permanent resident. Required: With reference to the relevant provisions under the Stamp Duty Ordinance, analyse whether ad valorem stamp duty, special stamp duty and buyer's stamp duty are payable on the agreement for sale and purchase and the transfer of shares, respectively. If so, compute the respective amounts payable. (9 marks)",
