      "prompt": "Module 9 (December 2022 Session) Page 8 of 11 (10) On 1 April 2020, Kate as the sole policy holder purchased a Qualifying Deferred Annuity Policy and paid qualifying annuity premiums of HK$40,000 and HK$20,000 on 1 April 2020 and 1 October 2020 respectively. Required: (a) Analyse, with reference to the relevant provisions under the IRO, whether Kate is chargeable to salaries tax for the years of assessment 2018/19, 2019/20 and 2020/21. (6 marks) (b) Assuming Kate is chargeable to salaries tax for the year of assessment 2020/21, calculate: (i) the share option gain chargeable to salaries tax for the year; and (3 marks) (ii) her salaries tax liability for the year. Ignore provisional salaries tax. (9 marks) Question 3 (9 marks – approximately 16 minutes) On 3 June 2020, Tony received a notice of estimated profits tax assessment for the year of assessment 2018/19 dated 1 June 2020. He told you that he was busy with his business and had failed to file the 2018/19 individual tax return. He said that the estimated assessment was excessive and his business was suffering losses. He wanted to dispute the assessment and he had no money to pay the tax demanded. Assume today is 10 June 2020. Tony approaches you for advice. Required: (a) Describe the requirements of a valid objection against an assessment as provided under the IRO. (6 marks) (b) Determine the deadline if Tony wants to lodge an objection against the estimated assessment. (1 mark) (c) List out the recovery actions (other than the imposition of surcharge) that can be taken by the CIR to recover the tax in default from Tony as provided under the IRO. (2 marks)",
