      "full": "Required:\n(a) Calculate the cost of common stock, cost of preferred stock and pre-tax cost of\ndebt for Kimberlite.\n(5 marks)\n(b) Calculate the weighted average cost of capital (\"WACC\") for Kimberlite.\n(4 marks)\n(c) Explain the \"Efficient Market Hypothesis\", list its THREE forms of market\nefficiency, and describe each of them respectively.\n(7 marks)\n(d) The management of Kimberlite is working on a restructuring plan which will have\na major impact on the profitability of the company. Assume a semi-strong\nefficient capital market, analyse the change in share price of Kimberlite under\nthe following circumstances:\n(i) The restructuring plan has just been approved by the board of directors of\nKimberlite but it has not been announced to the public yet.\n(2 marks)\n(ii) The restructuring plan has just been announced to the public.\n(2 marks)\nModule 7 (December 2023 Session) Page 2 of 8\nCPA hid pibiic Accountants\n-_ SERNGLR",
      "options": [
        "(a) Calculate the cost of common stock, cost of preferred stock and pre-tax cost of",
        "(b) Calculate the weighted average cost of capital (\"WACC\") for Kimberlite.",
        "(c) Explain the \"Efficient Market Hypothesis\", list its THREE forms of market",
        "(d) The management of Kimberlite is working on a restructuring plan which will have",
        "(i) The restructuring plan has just been approved by the board of directors of"
      ],
      "sourcePage": 2,
      "sourceMode": "ocr",
      "ocrUsed": true,
      "answer": "Module 7 (December 2023 Session) Page 7 of 7 Answer 4(b) Net working capital is defined as the current assets less the current liabilities. Working capital management refers to the day-to-day management of the company's current assets and liabilities. Working capital management is important because many businesses may be forced to go bankrupt due to the inability to meet short-term payment obligations even though the businesses are making a positive accounting profit. One of the objectives of managing working capital is to ensure the liquidity of the company. The company should have enough money to pay bills when they fall due. Otherwise, the company may be forced into compulsory liquidation to repay the outstanding liabilities. The other objective is to make sure that any spare cash should earn adequate interest by investing it as profitably as possible. Funds tied up in working capital may not earn the required return for the investors. Companies with high working capital may have a negative impact on the return on capital employed. * * * END OF EXAMINATION PAPER * * *",
      "answerSource": "",
      "hasAnswer": true
