      "ocrUsed": false,
      "answer": "Module 7 (December 2022 Session) Page 6 of 6 Answer 4(b)(i) After three months, the spot rate would be HK$8.80 x (1 + 5%) = HK$9.24. According to the forward contract, DML has to sell EUR200,000 using the forward rate of HK$8.60. If DML has not made the sales and will not receive the EUR200,000 in three months, it will have to buy EUR200,000 from the market to fulfil the forward contract. As such, the loss on the forward contract will be HK$(9.24 - 8.60) x 200,000 = HK$128,000. Answer 4(b)(ii) At the time DML enters into the forward contract, it has no idea what the exchange rate will be in the future. By making the overseas sales and owning the EUR200,000 receivable, DML will receive more in HK$ if EUR appreciates and will receive less in HK$ if EUR depreciates in three months. If EUR appreciates by 5% in three months, DML will receive more in HK$ (i.e, 200,000 x HK$9.24 = HK$1,848,000) on the receivable. However, the total cash receipts in HK$ will be offset by the loss on the forward contract (i.e., HK$128,000 as calculated in Question 4(b)(i) above). The total net amount received by DML will be HK$1,720,000 (HK$1,848,000 – HK$128,000). However, if EUR depreciates to a rate lower than the forward rate in three months, DML will receive less in HK$ on the receivable. Similarly, the total cash receipts in HK$ will be compensated by the gain on the forward contract. The total net amount received by DML will still be HK$1,720,000. The purpose of hedging with a forward contract is to ensure the value of the EUR200,000 receivable will be fixed in HK$ (i.e., HK$1,720,000 by converting the EUR200,000 at the contracted rate of HK$8.60) no matter whether the exchange rate between EUR and HK$ will go up or down in three months. As such, the future exchange rate is locked at the forward contract rate of HK$8.60 per EUR and the currency risk can be mitigated. Answer 4(b)(iii) Another major risk is the credit risk that DML's customer may not pay in three months. There are several ways to mitigate credit risk. Performing a credit check for the customer is the first step. DML can reduce its credit risk by obtaining credit insurance on the invoice issued to the customer. Shortening the payment may be another alternative. DML may also consider requesting a personal guarantee or a third-party guarantee from the customer. * * * END OF EXAMINATION PAPER * * *\nAfter three months, the spot rate would be HK$8.80 x (1 + 5%) = HK$9.24.\nAccording to the forward contract, DML has to sell EUR200,000 using the forward rate of HK$8.60.\nIf DML has not made the sales and will not receive the EUR200,000 in three months, it will have\nto buy EUR200,000 from the market to fulfil the forward contract. As such, the loss on the\nforward contract will be HK$(9.24 - 8.60) x 200,000 = HK$128,000.\nAt the time DML enters into the forward contract, it has no idea what the exchange rate will be in\nthe future. By making the overseas sales and owning the EUR200,000 receivable, DML will\nreceive more in HK$ if EUR appreciates and will receive less in HK$ if EUR depreciates in three\nmonths.\nIf EUR appreciates by 5% in three months, DML will receive more in HK$ (i.e, 200,000 x HK$9.24\n= HK$1,848,000) on the receivable. However, the total cash receipts in HK$ will be offset by the\nloss on the forward contract (i.e., HK$128,000 as calculated in Question 4(b)(i) above). The total\nnet amount received by DML will be HK$1,720,000 (HK$1,848,000 — HK$128,000).\nHowever, if EUR depreciates to a rate lower than the forward rate in three months, DML will receive\nless in HK$ on the receivable. Similarly, the total cash receipts in HK$ will be compensated by\nthe gain on the forward contract. The total net amount received by DML will still be\nHK$1,720,000.\nThe purpose of hedging with a forward contract is to ensure the value of the EUR200,000\nreceivable will be fixed in HK$ (i.e., HK$1,720,000 by converting the EUR200,000 at the contracted\nrate of HK$8.60) no matter whether the exchange rate between EUR and HK$ will go up or down\nin three months.\nAs such, the future exchange rate is locked at the forward contract rate of HK$8.60 per EUR and\nthe currency risk can be mitigated.\nAnother major risk is the credit risk that DML's customer may not pay in three months.\nThere are several ways to mitigate credit risk. Performing a credit check for the customer is the\nfirst step.\nDML can reduce its credit risk by obtaining credit insurance on the invoice issued to the customer.\nShortening the payment may be another alternative.\nDML may also consider requesting a personal guarantee or a third-party guarantee from the\ncustomer.\n* * * END OF EXAMINATION PAPER * * *\nModule 7 (December 2022 Session) Page 6 of 6\nCPA ies ribii Accountants\n- SEEeHILE",
