      "number": "1",
      "prompt": "Module 7 (December 2024 Session) Page 1 of 6 SECTION B – WRITTEN QUESTIONS ( Total: 80 marks ) Answer ALL questions in this section. Marks are indicated at the end of each question. Together they are worth 80% of the total marks for this examination. Question 1 (20 marks – approximately 36 minutes) You have savings of HK$100,000 and want to invest in two securities listed on the stock exchange of Hong Kong. You have done some research on the internet and have obtained the following information: State of the economy Probability of occurrence Stock A expected return Stock B expected return Boom 20% - 8% 30% Normal 50% 10% 15% Recession 30% 15% - 12% Required: (a) Compute the expected returns on stock A and stock B, respectively. (3 marks) (b) Compute the standard deviations of the returns on stock A and stock B, respectively. (3 marks) (c) Calculate the composition (i.e., the weights for stock A and stock B, respectively) of the portfolio if you want to achieve an expected return of 9%. (3 marks) (d) Calculate the correlation coefficient between stock A and stock B. (4 marks) (e) For the \"correlation coefficient\" between two stocks: (i) Explain what it is and its value range. (4 marks) (ii) Explain its impact on the risk diversification effects on a portfolio comprising two stocks without referring to the above answers calculated in this question. (3 marks)",
      "full": "Module 7 (December 2024 Session) Page 1 of 6 SECTION B – WRITTEN QUESTIONS ( Total: 80 marks ) Answer ALL questions in this section. Marks are indicated at the end of each question. Together they are worth 80% of the total marks for this examination. Question 1 (20 marks – approximately 36 minutes) You have savings of HK$100,000 and want to invest in two securities listed on the stock exchange of Hong Kong. You have done some research on the internet and have obtained the following information: State of the economy Probability of occurrence Stock A expected return Stock B expected return Boom 20% - 8% 30% Normal 50% 10% 15% Recession 30% 15% - 12% Required: (a) Compute the expected returns on stock A and stock B, respectively. (3 marks) (b) Compute the standard deviations of the returns on stock A and stock B, respectively. (3 marks) (c) Calculate the composition (i.e., the weights for stock A and stock B, respectively) of the portfolio if you want to achieve an expected return of 9%. (3 marks) (d) Calculate the correlation coefficient between stock A and stock B. (4 marks) (e) For the \"correlation coefficient\" between two stocks: (i) Explain what it is and its value range. (4 marks) (ii) Explain its impact on the risk diversification effects on a portfolio comprising two stocks without referring to the above answers calculated in this question. (3 marks)",
      "options": [],
      "sourcePage": 1,
      "sourceMode": "text",
      "ocrUsed": false,
      "answer": "Module 7 (December 2024 Session) Page 7 of 7 Many companies have minimum expectations of the values of RI for their operations and investments. Economic Value added (EVA) Economic value added (EVA) is a type of residual income incorporating several adjustments to lower some of the disadvantages created by residual income. The EVA is calculated as: EVA = Adjusted after-tax operating income - [WACC x (Adjusted total assets - Current liabilities)] EVA solved the problems that financial measures based on profits calculated in accordance with accounting standards do not truly reflect the wealth created by the company and are subject to manipulation by the management. * * * END OF EXAMINATION PAPER * * *\nMany companies have minimum expectations of the values of RI for their operations and\ninvestments.\nEconomic Value added (EVA)\nEconomic value added (EVA) is a type of residual income incorporating several adjustments to\nlower some of the disadvantages created by residual income.\nThe EVAis calculated as:\nEVA = Adjusted after-tax operating income - [WACC x (Adjusted total assets - Current liabilities)]\nEVA solved the problems that financial measures based on profits calculated in accordance with\naccounting standards do not truly reflect the wealth created by the company and are subject to\nmanipulation by the management.\n* * * END OF EXAMINATION PAPER * * *\nModule 7 (December 2024 Session) Page 7 of 7\nCPA iid runic Accountants\n- SEEeHILE",
      "answerSource": "",
      "hasAnswer": true
