      "full": "Module 7 (December 2024 Session) Page 5 of 6 Question 4 (20 marks – approximately 36 minutes) Jupiter Limited (\"Jupiter\") is an original equipment manufacturer (\"OEM\") selling electronic components and products. In order to upgrade its production capacity, Jupiter purchased a new production line in 2023. The cost of this production line is HK$200 million, which was 100% financed by a bank loan. The latest financials for the last two years are as follows: Statements of Profit or Loss for the year ended 31 December 2023 2022 HK$m HK$m Net sales 2,230 2,050 Cost of goods sold 1,710 1,580 Gross profit 520 470 Operating costs 188 145 Depreciation 97 82 Profit before interest and tax 235 243 Interest expenses 56 45 Profit before tax 179 198 Tax expenses 30 33 Net income 149 165 Dividends 45 50 Retained profit 104 115 Statements of Financial Position as at 31 December 2023 2022 HK$m HK$m Non-current assets 2,286 2,176 Current assets Inventories 486 375 Accounts receivable 195 160 Cash 141 74 822 609 Total assets 3,108 2,785 Non-current liabilities 1,000 800 Current liabilities Accounts payable 352 339 Other payables 192 186 544 525 Share capital 1,000 1,000 Retained earnings 564 460 Total equity 1,564 1,460 Total liabilities and equity 3,108 2,785",
      "options": [],
      "sourcePage": 5,
      "sourceMode": "text",
      "ocrUsed": false,
      "answer": "Module 7 (December 2024 Session) Page 7 of 7 Many companies have minimum expectations of the values of RI for their operations and investments. Economic Value added (EVA) Economic value added (EVA) is a type of residual income incorporating several adjustments to lower some of the disadvantages created by residual income. The EVA is calculated as: EVA = Adjusted after-tax operating income - [WACC x (Adjusted total assets - Current liabilities)] EVA solved the problems that financial measures based on profits calculated in accordance with accounting standards do not truly reflect the wealth created by the company and are subject to manipulation by the management. * * * END OF EXAMINATION PAPER * * *\nMany companies have minimum expectations of the values of RI for their operations and\ninvestments.\nEconomic Value added (EVA)\nEconomic value added (EVA) is a type of residual income incorporating several adjustments to\nlower some of the disadvantages created by residual income.\nThe EVAis calculated as:\nEVA = Adjusted after-tax operating income - [WACC x (Adjusted total assets - Current liabilities)]\nEVA solved the problems that financial measures based on profits calculated in accordance with\naccounting standards do not truly reflect the wealth created by the company and are subject to\nmanipulation by the management.\n* * * END OF EXAMINATION PAPER * * *\nModule 7 (December 2024 Session) Page 7 of 7\nCPA iid runic Accountants\n- SEEeHILE",
