      "number": "1",
      "prompt": "Module 6 (December 2020 Session) Page 3 of 7 Question 2 (20 marks – approximately 36 minutes) Sunlight Cosmetics Limited (\"SUL\") is a toy manufacturer. SUL manufactures toys in its own plants and distributes the finished products through its own networks. The unadjusted trial balance for SUL at 31 March 2019 is as follows: DR CR HK$'000 HK$'000 Sales - 155,400 Costs of goods manufactured in the year to 31 March 2019 (excluding depreciation) 104,500 - Distribution costs 10,560 - Administrative expenses 23,120 - Other expenses 3,400 - Interest received - 11,700 8% bank loan interest paid 1,120 - Land and buildings (including land HK$60 million) 80,800 - Plant and equipment 15,220 - Accumulated depreciation as at 31 March 2018 Buildings - 7,560 Plant and equipment - 3,170 Inventories as at 31 March 2018 6,352 - Trade receivables 24,830 - Bank and cash 23,190 - Ordinary shares, fully paid - 33,930 7% redeemable preference shares - 2,600 Revaluation surplus - 4,635 Retained earnings, 31 March 2018 - 38,637 Ordinary dividends paid 2,500 - Preference dividends paid 182 - 8% bank loan - 28,000 Trade payables - 10,142 295,774 295,774 Additional information: (i) On 31 March 2019, the company is being sued by a supplier for breach of contract. The supplier sued the company for a claim of HK$10 million. According to the legal opinion, it is highly likely that the company will lose the case and be required to pay the claimed amount. The case will be concluded within the next accounting period. (ii) The preference shares will be redeemed for HK$2,600,000 in 2022. Preference dividends are paid on 31 March each year. (iii) Buildings are depreciated on a straight-line basis at a rate of 5% per annum. Depreciation on buildings is classified as administrative expenses.",
