      "id": "file:///F:/hkicpa%20LP+Past%20paper/M1-10LP+Past%20paper/1-10%20Past%20paper/m6/Module%206%20Question%20Dec%202020.pdf#question-q-p005-1",
      "number": "1",
      "prompt": "Module 6 (December 2020 Session) Page 5 of 7 Question 3 (10 marks – approximately 18 minutes) Bob Limited (\"BOL\") is a toy manufacturer and retailer operating in Hong Kong. During the reporting period ended 31 December 2019, the following events occurred. Machinery: BOL decided to revise the useful life and residual value of its machinery due to wear and tear. The machinery was purchased on 1 January 2015 at a cost of HK$2,600,000. At the time of acquisition, the estimated useful life of the machinery was 10 years and the residual value was HK$500,000. On 31 December 2018, the estimated useful life was revised from 10 years to 8 years and residual value became HK$300,000. The machinery is depreciated on a straight- line basis. Inventory: BOL changed its inventory valuation method from FIFO to weighted average cost for the purpose of providing more relevant and comparable information to financial statement users. Such change has resulted in the following revision of financial figures: For the period ending 31 December 2018 For all periods prior to 2018 Cost of Goods Sold HK$600,000 increase HK$2,800,000 increase Inventory HK$600,000 decrease HK$2,800,000 decrease The following additional information is also available to BOL:  Retained earnings at 31 December 2017 was HK$15,700,000.  Profit (after taxes) for the year ended 31 December 2018 and 31 December 2019 was HK$1,430,000 and HK$1,690,000, respectively.  The income tax rate is 16.5%.  No dividends have been declared or paid during the current period.  Assume all amounts are material. Required: In accordance with HKAS 8 Accounting Policies, Changes in Accounting Estimates and Errors , ignoring deferred tax, (a) Explain how BOL should account for the machinery in the preparation of the financial statements for the year ended 31 December 2019. Support your answers with calculations. (4 marks) (b) Explain how BOL should account for the inventory in the preparation of the financial statements for the year ended 31 December 2019. Prepare an extract of the statement of changes in equity for the year ended 31 December 2019 to demonstrate the inventory effects. (6 marks)",
      "full": "Module 6 (December 2020 Session) Page 5 of 7 Question 3 (10 marks – approximately 18 minutes) Bob Limited (\"BOL\") is a toy manufacturer and retailer operating in Hong Kong. During the reporting period ended 31 December 2019, the following events occurred. Machinery: BOL decided to revise the useful life and residual value of its machinery due to wear and tear. The machinery was purchased on 1 January 2015 at a cost of HK$2,600,000. At the time of acquisition, the estimated useful life of the machinery was 10 years and the residual value was HK$500,000. On 31 December 2018, the estimated useful life was revised from 10 years to 8 years and residual value became HK$300,000. The machinery is depreciated on a straight- line basis. Inventory: BOL changed its inventory valuation method from FIFO to weighted average cost for the purpose of providing more relevant and comparable information to financial statement users. Such change has resulted in the following revision of financial figures: For the period ending 31 December 2018 For all periods prior to 2018 Cost of Goods Sold HK$600,000 increase HK$2,800,000 increase Inventory HK$600,000 decrease HK$2,800,000 decrease The following additional information is also available to BOL:  Retained earnings at 31 December 2017 was HK$15,700,000.  Profit (after taxes) for the year ended 31 December 2018 and 31 December 2019 was HK$1,430,000 and HK$1,690,000, respectively.  The income tax rate is 16.5%.  No dividends have been declared or paid during the current period.  Assume all amounts are material. Required: In accordance with HKAS 8 Accounting Policies, Changes in Accounting Estimates and Errors , ignoring deferred tax, (a) Explain how BOL should account for the machinery in the preparation of the financial statements for the year ended 31 December 2019. Support your answers with calculations. (4 marks) (b) Explain how BOL should account for the inventory in the preparation of the financial statements for the year ended 31 December 2019. Prepare an extract of the statement of changes in equity for the year ended 31 December 2019 to demonstrate the inventory effects. (6 marks)",
