      "sourceMode": "text",
      "ocrUsed": false,
      "answer": "Module 3 (December 2020 Session) Page 9 of 9 Answer 5(a) A point estimate for a population parameter, such as the population mean, is the (unbiased) single number estimate of that parameter. A confidence interval, on the other hand, is a range of values for the population parameter with a level of confidence that the range or interval contains the parameter, such as population mean. Answer 5(b) p = 230/300 = 0.7666, n=300, Z 0.05 = 1.96 95% C.I. of population proportion of employees = (0.7666 – 1.96 √ 0.7666 ( 1 – 0.7666 ) 300 , 0.7666 + 1.96 √ 0.7666 ( 1 – 0.7666 ) 300 ) = (0.7666 – 0.0479, 0.7666 + 0.0479) = (0.7187, 0.8145) * * * END OF EXAMINATION PAPER * * *\nA point estimate for a population parameter, such as the population mean, is the (unbiased)\nsingle number estimate of that parameter.\nA confidence interval, on the other hand, is a range of values for the population parameter\nwith a level of confidence that the range or interval contains the parameter, such as population\nmean.\np =230/300 = 0.7666, n=300, Zoos = 1.96\n95% C.I. of population proportion of employees\n_ 0.7666(1 — 0.7666) 0.7666(1 — 0.7666)\n= (0.7666 — 1.96 — 0.7666 + 1.96 0)\n= (0.7666 — 0.0479, 0.7666 + 0.0479)\n=(0.7187, 0.8145)\n* * * END OF EXAMINATION PAPER * * *",
