      "number": "1",
      "prompt": "Module 3 (December 2022 Session) Page 1 of 5 SECTION B – WRITTEN QUESTIONS (Total: 80 marks) Answer ALL questions in this section. Marks are indicated at the end of each question. Together they are worth 80% of the total marks for this examination. Question 1 (24 marks – approximately 43 minutes) You are researching the movie theater industry in Country A. Specifically, you are assessing the potential impacts of two events that are taking place simultaneously in the country: Event (I) Int'lCin, an international film and television production and distribution company, is opening multi-screen movie theaters in most of the country's first-tier cities. Event (II) Movie theaters (existing and the new ones) are raising the price of snacks (such as popcorn and soft drinks) by an average of 30 percent. Required: (a) Define substitutes and complements in consumption. (2 marks) (b) State any THREE factors that would generally cause: (i) a change in demand; (ii) a change in supply. (3 marks) (c) Describe how the Latin phrase \"ceteris paribus\" (meaning all other factors being equal) can be used to explain the difference in \"change in demand\" and \"change in quantity demanded\". (2 marks) (d) Analyse how (the channel through which) Event (I) would affect the demand and/or supply of the movie tickets (seats). NO diagram is required. (2 marks) (e) Analyse how Event (II) would affect the demand and/or supply of the movie tickets. NO diagram is required. (3 marks) (f) Suppose you estimated the cross-price elasticity between movie tickets and snack price to be 0.7 (stated in ABSOLUTE value), analyse (with calculations support) how the movie ticket sales are affected by Event (II). (4 marks) (g) Analyse how the equilibrium price and quantity (sold) of movie tickets are affected by the impacts of the two events by filling in the following table: Direction of Price Change Direction of Quantity Change Event (I): ( ) ( ) Event (II): ( ) ( ) Net effect: ( ) ( ) (8 marks)",
      "full": "Module 3 (December 2022 Session) Page 1 of 5 SECTION B – WRITTEN QUESTIONS (Total: 80 marks) Answer ALL questions in this section. Marks are indicated at the end of each question. Together they are worth 80% of the total marks for this examination. Question 1 (24 marks – approximately 43 minutes) You are researching the movie theater industry in Country A. Specifically, you are assessing the potential impacts of two events that are taking place simultaneously in the country: Event (I) Int'lCin, an international film and television production and distribution company, is opening multi-screen movie theaters in most of the country's first-tier cities. Event (II) Movie theaters (existing and the new ones) are raising the price of snacks (such as popcorn and soft drinks) by an average of 30 percent. Required: (a) Define substitutes and complements in consumption. (2 marks) (b) State any THREE factors that would generally cause: (i) a change in demand; (ii) a change in supply. (3 marks) (c) Describe how the Latin phrase \"ceteris paribus\" (meaning all other factors being equal) can be used to explain the difference in \"change in demand\" and \"change in quantity demanded\". (2 marks) (d) Analyse how (the channel through which) Event (I) would affect the demand and/or supply of the movie tickets (seats). NO diagram is required. (2 marks) (e) Analyse how Event (II) would affect the demand and/or supply of the movie tickets. NO diagram is required. (3 marks) (f) Suppose you estimated the cross-price elasticity between movie tickets and snack price to be 0.7 (stated in ABSOLUTE value), analyse (with calculations support) how the movie ticket sales are affected by Event (II). (4 marks) (g) Analyse how the equilibrium price and quantity (sold) of movie tickets are affected by the impacts of the two events by filling in the following table: Direction of Price Change Direction of Quantity Change Event (I): ( ) ( ) Event (II): ( ) ( ) Net effect: ( ) ( ) (8 marks)",
      "options": [],
      "sourcePage": 1,
