      "prompt": "Module 3 (December 2022 Session) Page 2 of 5 Question 2 (24 marks – approximately 43 minutes) Inflation and supply-chain disruptions are the buzzwords that have been dominating the news headlines in various countries over the past few months. Investors of all stripes have been paying close attention to how the unfolding of events would affect the world economy and the subsequent impacts brought about by government policy responses, especially those of central banks across the globe. Required: (a) Define inflation, stagnation and stagflation. (4 marks) (b) (i) Justify why economists generally consider Consumer Price Index (CPI) an appropriate measure of consumers' cost of living. (2 marks) (ii) Describe the potential problem of CPI that may undermine its usefulness as a measure of cost of living for guiding government welfare policy. (2 marks) (c) Inflation is costly to society and the economy but does not affect every group of economic agents evenly. (i) Analyse the costs of inflation in terms of its redistribution effects, and deadweight loss effects. (4 marks) (ii) State and describe any ONE example of the redistributive effects of inflation. (2 marks) (d) The aggregate demand-aggregate supply (AD-AS) model is a macroeconomic model used to explain the relationship between price level and output of an economy. (i) Apply the AD-AS model to explain how supply chain disruption may result in stagflation. (2 marks) (ii) Explain the two types of inflation in an AD-AS context. (4 marks) (iii) In general, economists are pessimistic about the use of monetary policy in tackling stagflation. Use the AD-AS model to justify this view. (4 marks)",
