      "number": "1",
      "prompt": "Module 3 (June 2021 Session) Page 1 of 5 SECTION B – WRITTEN QUESTIONS (Total: 80 marks) Answer ALL questions in this section. Marks are indicated at the end of each question. Together they are worth 80% of the total marks for this examination. Question 1 (21 marks – approximately 38 minutes) (a) The following functions represent the market for wheat in Country A: Q(s) = 150 + 30P Q(d) = 500 – 40P where P is the price per bushel of wheat. Required: (i) Solve for the market equilibrium. (3 marks) (ii) If the government controls the price of wheat at HK$4 per bushel, calculate the amount of excess demand or excess supply at a price of HK$4. (4 marks) (iii) State the TWO major forms of price controls. (2 marks) (iv) State any ONE market-failure related cause that explains the type of price control adopted by government in part (a)(ii) and the market practice likely to emerge as a result. (2 marks) (b) Analyse the change in the equilibrium price and quantity in a competitive automotive market in each of the following cases. Note: No graphical support is required. Required: (i) The terrorist attacks in some petroleum refinery facilities in the Middle East triggered the increase in price of gasoline. (5 marks) (ii) The market price of steel has increased significantly. (5 marks)",
      "full": "Module 3 (June 2021 Session) Page 1 of 5 SECTION B – WRITTEN QUESTIONS (Total: 80 marks) Answer ALL questions in this section. Marks are indicated at the end of each question. Together they are worth 80% of the total marks for this examination. Question 1 (21 marks – approximately 38 minutes) (a) The following functions represent the market for wheat in Country A: Q(s) = 150 + 30P Q(d) = 500 – 40P where P is the price per bushel of wheat. Required: (i) Solve for the market equilibrium. (3 marks) (ii) If the government controls the price of wheat at HK$4 per bushel, calculate the amount of excess demand or excess supply at a price of HK$4. (4 marks) (iii) State the TWO major forms of price controls. (2 marks) (iv) State any ONE market-failure related cause that explains the type of price control adopted by government in part (a)(ii) and the market practice likely to emerge as a result. (2 marks) (b) Analyse the change in the equilibrium price and quantity in a competitive automotive market in each of the following cases. Note: No graphical support is required. Required: (i) The terrorist attacks in some petroleum refinery facilities in the Middle East triggered the increase in price of gasoline. (5 marks) (ii) The market price of steel has increased significantly. (5 marks)",
      "options": [],
      "sourcePage": 1,
      "sourceMode": "text",
      "ocrUsed": false,
      "answer": "Module 3 (June 2021 Session) Page 5 of 5 Answer 4 ( a ) (i ii ) Pro bability sampling met hods:  Simple random sampling: Each unit in the population has an equal chance of being selected.  Systematic sampling: Each member of the entire population is first numbered and then sample members are chosen based on a random starting point but with a fixed interval.  Cluster sampling: Divides a population into groups (clusters) that are representative of the population and then studies the selected clusters.  Stratified sampling: Divides a population into groups (strata) that share a characteristic of interest and then draws a random sample from each strata. [Any two of the above] [Other valid methods are also acceptable] Answer 4 ( b ) A public good has the defining characteristics of being non - excludable and non - rivalrous. Non-excludable means it is impossible or prohibitively costly for the owner to exclude others from using the good. Non-rival means that one person's use of a good does not preclude others from using it. Answer 4 ( c ) Jocelyn's first choice is to work full time as a consultant. Her next best opportunity/ alternative is teaching summer courses and travelling for the remainder of the summer. Therefore, Jocelyn's opportunity cost of being a consultant is the HK$20,000 she would have earned from teaching, as well as the satisfaction she could have derived from travelling. * * * END OF EXAMINATION PAPER * * *\nProbability sampling methods:",
