      "number": "1",
      "prompt": "Module 3 (June 2021 Session) Page 3 of 5 Question 3 (19 marks – approximately 34 minutes) Country X consumes a lot of chocolate bars. In 2019, the country consumed 100 Venus chocolate bars for HK$9 each and 200 Bradbury hazelnut chocolate bars for HK$10 each. In 2020, the country consumed 130 Venus chocolate bars for HK$10 each and 220 packs of Bradbury hazelnut chocolate bars for HK$12 each. Required: (a) Year 2019 is the base year. Compute the following price indices for years 2019 and 2020:  GDP Deflator; and  Consumer Price Index. (8 marks) (b) Based on the TWO indices above, compute the percentage change in price between 2019 and 2020. Analyse the differences between the TWO answers. (7 marks) (c) From an economist's viewpoint, explain which of the above indices is considered a better measure of the cost of Country X's chocolate bar consumption over time. Assume that there are rival brands of chocolate bar in the market. (4 marks)",
      "full": "Module 3 (June 2021 Session) Page 3 of 5 Question 3 (19 marks – approximately 34 minutes) Country X consumes a lot of chocolate bars. In 2019, the country consumed 100 Venus chocolate bars for HK$9 each and 200 Bradbury hazelnut chocolate bars for HK$10 each. In 2020, the country consumed 130 Venus chocolate bars for HK$10 each and 220 packs of Bradbury hazelnut chocolate bars for HK$12 each. Required: (a) Year 2019 is the base year. Compute the following price indices for years 2019 and 2020:  GDP Deflator; and  Consumer Price Index. (8 marks) (b) Based on the TWO indices above, compute the percentage change in price between 2019 and 2020. Analyse the differences between the TWO answers. (7 marks) (c) From an economist's viewpoint, explain which of the above indices is considered a better measure of the cost of Country X's chocolate bar consumption over time. Assume that there are rival brands of chocolate bar in the market. (4 marks)",
      "options": [],
      "sourcePage": 3,
      "sourceMode": "text",
      "ocrUsed": false,
      "answer": "Module 3 (June 2021 Session) Page 5 of 5 Answer 4 ( a ) (i ii ) Pro bability sampling met hods:  Simple random sampling: Each unit in the population has an equal chance of being selected.  Systematic sampling: Each member of the entire population is first numbered and then sample members are chosen based on a random starting point but with a fixed interval.  Cluster sampling: Divides a population into groups (clusters) that are representative of the population and then studies the selected clusters.  Stratified sampling: Divides a population into groups (strata) that share a characteristic of interest and then draws a random sample from each strata. [Any two of the above] [Other valid methods are also acceptable] Answer 4 ( b ) A public good has the defining characteristics of being non - excludable and non - rivalrous. Non-excludable means it is impossible or prohibitively costly for the owner to exclude others from using the good. Non-rival means that one person's use of a good does not preclude others from using it. Answer 4 ( c ) Jocelyn's first choice is to work full time as a consultant. Her next best opportunity/ alternative is teaching summer courses and travelling for the remainder of the summer. Therefore, Jocelyn's opportunity cost of being a consultant is the HK$20,000 she would have earned from teaching, as well as the satisfaction she could have derived from travelling. * * * END OF EXAMINATION PAPER * * *\nProbability sampling methods:",
