      "sourceMatch": "Module 13 (December 2024 Session) Page 1 of 11 SECTION A – CASE QUESTIONS ( TOTAL: 50 marks ) Answer ALL of the following questions. Marks will be awarded for logical argumentation",
      "id": "file:///F:/hkicpa%20LP+Past%20paper/11-14LP+Past%20paper/m13past%20paper/M13/M13%20Dec%2024%20Question.pdf#question-q-p001-1",
      "number": "1",
      "prompt": "Module 13 (December 2024 Session) Page 1 of 11 SECTION A – CASE QUESTIONS ( TOTAL: 50 marks ) Answer ALL of the following questions. Marks will be awarded for logical argumentation/ calculation and appropriate presentation of the answers. CASE Jeng Grocery (\"Jeng\") was set up in Hong Kong last year. It sells grocery items through its online mobile application and physical kiosks. Jeng is owned by a few shareholders, including certain private equity funds, and has a small management team. This team is comprised of the Chief Executive Officer, Chief Finance Officer and other senior management personnel who are responsible for all sales, marketing, accounting, finance and administrative matters. Several senior management personnel are the related parties of Jeng. Jeng's shareholders have set aggressive sales targets in the first five years. To meet these targets, Jeng has implemented an incentive program where senior management personnel may receive a discretionary bonus depending on Jeng's sales achieved. Jeng sells its own purchased goods and consignment goods for various local and overseas brands. It faces severe competition in the industry because several competing large grocery stores have been dominant in the market for a considerable amount of time. However, Jeng offers a wide range of goods and an online sales platform, which may make it better suited than competitors to meet the needs of young couples. After only a year of operation, Jeng has become one of the top 10 grocery retailers in Hong Kong and has approximately 1 million registered members. Jeng has now set up more than 50 self-service kiosks in Hong Kong which cover all major residential areas. Nevertheless, due to incurring significant start-up costs, Jeng is still loss-making. Management expects Jeng to become profitable when it attains a larger market share and membership numbers. To ensure healthy growth, management is currently looking for new investors to inject capital into Jeng. Below is an extract of the segmental financial information that management has prepared for Jeng's potential investors: Sale of Goods HK$'000 Consignment Sales HK$'000 2024 Total HK$'000 Revenue 300,000 85,000 385,000 Less: Cost of sales (150,000) - (150,000) Less: Selling and distribution expenses (100,000) (45,000) (145,000) 50,000 40,000 90,000 Less: Administrative expense (85,000) Less: Other expenses (55,000) Loss for the period (50,000)",
      "full": "Module 13 (December 2024 Session) Page 1 of 11 SECTION A – CASE QUESTIONS ( TOTAL: 50 marks ) Answer ALL of the following questions. Marks will be awarded for logical argumentation/ calculation and appropriate presentation of the answers. CASE Jeng Grocery (\"Jeng\") was set up in Hong Kong last year. It sells grocery items through its online mobile application and physical kiosks. Jeng is owned by a few shareholders, including certain private equity funds, and has a small management team. This team is comprised of the Chief Executive Officer, Chief Finance Officer and other senior management personnel who are responsible for all sales, marketing, accounting, finance and administrative matters. Several senior management personnel are the related parties of Jeng. Jeng's shareholders have set aggressive sales targets in the first five years. To meet these targets, Jeng has implemented an incentive program where senior management personnel may receive a discretionary bonus depending on Jeng's sales achieved. Jeng sells its own purchased goods and consignment goods for various local and overseas brands. It faces severe competition in the industry because several competing large grocery stores have been dominant in the market for a considerable amount of time. However, Jeng offers a wide range of goods and an online sales platform, which may make it better suited than competitors to meet the needs of young couples. After only a year of operation, Jeng has become one of the top 10 grocery retailers in Hong Kong and has approximately 1 million registered members. Jeng has now set up more than 50 self-service kiosks in Hong Kong which cover all major residential areas. Nevertheless, due to incurring significant start-up costs, Jeng is still loss-making. Management expects Jeng to become profitable when it attains a larger market share and membership numbers. To ensure healthy growth, management is currently looking for new investors to inject capital into Jeng. Below is an extract of the segmental financial information that management has prepared for Jeng's potential investors: Sale of Goods HK$'000 Consignment Sales HK$'000 2024 Total HK$'000 Revenue 300,000 85,000 385,000 Less: Cost of sales (150,000) - (150,000) Less: Selling and distribution expenses (100,000) (45,000) (145,000) 50,000 40,000 90,000 Less: Administrative expense (85,000) Less: Other expenses (55,000) Loss for the period (50,000)",
