      "sourceMatch": "Module 13 (December 2024 Session) Page 6 of 11 Question 4 (12 marks – approximately 22 minutes) As set out in the case background, the sales of Jeng's own goods are recorded at \"gr",
      "id": "file:///F:/hkicpa%20LP+Past%20paper/11-14LP+Past%20paper/m13past%20paper/M13/M13%20Dec%2024%20Question.pdf#question-q-p006-1",
      "number": "1",
      "prompt": "Module 13 (December 2024 Session) Page 6 of 11 Question 4 (12 marks – approximately 22 minutes) As set out in the case background, the sales of Jeng's own goods are recorded at \"gross\" amount and the consignment sales are recorded at \"net\" sales amount, which represented the commission income. To adjust the consignment sales from a \"gross\" to a \"net\" basis, each month the accounting team will post a manual journal entry to adjust the sales amount of the monthly consignment sales to the commission income. This manual journal entry is posted by the accounting team at each month's end directly to the general ledger upon closing the financial statements. Below are the hypothetical entries (assuming a sales item of HK$100 and therefore a net commission income of HK$10): Entry #1 (When goods are sold to customer) Dr. Cash HK$100 Cr. Revenue HK$100 Entry #2 (To adjust the gross revenue to a net commission) Dr. Revenue HK$90 Cr. Payable to principal HK$90 The resulting revenue of consignment sales therefore will record HK$10 (i.e. \"net\" basis) instead of HK$100 (i.e. \"gross\" basis) in the revenue account. During the audit, the audit team obtained the list of these manual journal entries and noted that 12 manual entries relating to the \"gross\" vs \"net\" on consignment sales were posted at each month-end. However, the audit team also found that, in addition to these 12 manual entries, the accounting team posted 50 other journal entries, all of which were credited to the revenue account, and the amounts of some of these journal entries are significant. Although the presentation of the consignment sales at gross amount does not have any impact on the net profit, it would still materially impact Jeng's financial statements if manual entry #2 is not properly posted. Further, through the posting of the 50 other manual entries which were credited to the revenue account, it may provide opportunities for management to overstate its revenue by recording inappropriate journal entries. Required: Prepare a memo to the audit partner suggesting audit procedures to test (i) the 12 manual entries on the consignment sales, and proposing any other work to ensure the consignment sales are presented at a \"net\" basis; and (ii) the 50 other manual entries which were credited to the revenue account. Explain your rationale in the memo. Note: A maximum of 2 marks for communication skills and 2 marks for analytical skills will be awarded. (12 marks) * * * * * * *",
      "full": "Module 13 (December 2024 Session) Page 6 of 11 Question 4 (12 marks – approximately 22 minutes) As set out in the case background, the sales of Jeng's own goods are recorded at \"gross\" amount and the consignment sales are recorded at \"net\" sales amount, which represented the commission income. To adjust the consignment sales from a \"gross\" to a \"net\" basis, each month the accounting team will post a manual journal entry to adjust the sales amount of the monthly consignment sales to the commission income. This manual journal entry is posted by the accounting team at each month's end directly to the general ledger upon closing the financial statements. Below are the hypothetical entries (assuming a sales item of HK$100 and therefore a net commission income of HK$10): Entry #1 (When goods are sold to customer) Dr. Cash HK$100 Cr. Revenue HK$100 Entry #2 (To adjust the gross revenue to a net commission) Dr. Revenue HK$90 Cr. Payable to principal HK$90 The resulting revenue of consignment sales therefore will record HK$10 (i.e. \"net\" basis) instead of HK$100 (i.e. \"gross\" basis) in the revenue account. During the audit, the audit team obtained the list of these manual journal entries and noted that 12 manual entries relating to the \"gross\" vs \"net\" on consignment sales were posted at each month-end. However, the audit team also found that, in addition to these 12 manual entries, the accounting team posted 50 other journal entries, all of which were credited to the revenue account, and the amounts of some of these journal entries are significant. Although the presentation of the consignment sales at gross amount does not have any impact on the net profit, it would still materially impact Jeng's financial statements if manual entry #2 is not properly posted. Further, through the posting of the 50 other manual entries which were credited to the revenue account, it may provide opportunities for management to overstate its revenue by recording inappropriate journal entries. Required: Prepare a memo to the audit partner suggesting audit procedures to test (i) the 12 manual entries on the consignment sales, and proposing any other work to ensure the consignment sales are presented at a \"net\" basis; and (ii) the 50 other manual entries which were credited to the revenue account. Explain your rationale in the memo. Note: A maximum of 2 marks for communication skills and 2 marks for analytical skills will be awarded. (12 marks) * * * * * * *",
