      "number": "1",
      "prompt": "Module C (December 2019 Session) Page 1 of 9 SECTION A – CASE QUESTIONS (Total 50 marks) Answer ALL of the following questions. Marks will be awarded for logical argumentation and appropriate presentation of the answers. CASE Fortune Cleaning Services Limited ( “ Fortune ” ) was established in Hong Kong . It is a private company engaged in cleaning services. Fortune ’ s customers are mainly retailers . It has achieved a year - to - year growth in sales of 25% during the last five years. Service contracts can be structured on a project basis, monthly basis or yearly basis , depending on the request from its customers. Starting from December 2019, its sales have doubled compared to the sales in November 2019 because Fortune has commenced a new service contract with a retail chain comprising a network of 60 outlets. Staff costs are Fortune ’ s largest cost component. The relevant financial information of Fortune ’ s staff costs for the fiscal years 2018 and 2019 are shown below: 2019 HK$ ’ 000 2018 HK$ ’ 000 % Increase/ (decrease) Direct labour wages 18,035 12,882 40% Management compensation 4,888 5,200 (6%) Administrative staff salaries 5,341 4,951 8% Discretionary bonus 2,453 2,328 5% Retirement benefits 371 344 8% Total staff costs 31,088 25,705 21% Total costs 41,451 34,736 19% Sales 49,746 39,646 25% Profit before tax 6,790 4,184 62% Fortune has three types of employees: direct labour (i.e. workers), administrative staff and the management. The workers work on the part-time basis. Every day, a project supervisor records the names and the working hours of each worker in a job order register. The project supervisor is also responsible for the daily physical head counts. The project supervisor submits the job order register to the account clerk for calculating the wages. Wages for workers are paid on the 25 th of each month by cash through cash withdrawal by the account clerk. To simplify the process, the account clerk records the monthly wages of these part-time workers on cash basis.",
      "full": "Module C (December 2019 Session) Page 1 of 9 SECTION A – CASE QUESTIONS (Total 50 marks) Answer ALL of the following questions. Marks will be awarded for logical argumentation and appropriate presentation of the answers. CASE Fortune Cleaning Services Limited ( “ Fortune ” ) was established in Hong Kong . It is a private company engaged in cleaning services. Fortune ’ s customers are mainly retailers . It has achieved a year - to - year growth in sales of 25% during the last five years. Service contracts can be structured on a project basis, monthly basis or yearly basis , depending on the request from its customers. Starting from December 2019, its sales have doubled compared to the sales in November 2019 because Fortune has commenced a new service contract with a retail chain comprising a network of 60 outlets. Staff costs are Fortune ’ s largest cost component. The relevant financial information of Fortune ’ s staff costs for the fiscal years 2018 and 2019 are shown below: 2019 HK$ ’ 000 2018 HK$ ’ 000 % Increase/ (decrease) Direct labour wages 18,035 12,882 40% Management compensation 4,888 5,200 (6%) Administrative staff salaries 5,341 4,951 8% Discretionary bonus 2,453 2,328 5% Retirement benefits 371 344 8% Total staff costs 31,088 25,705 21% Total costs 41,451 34,736 19% Sales 49,746 39,646 25% Profit before tax 6,790 4,184 62% Fortune has three types of employees: direct labour (i.e. workers), administrative staff and the management. The workers work on the part-time basis. Every day, a project supervisor records the names and the working hours of each worker in a job order register. The project supervisor is also responsible for the daily physical head counts. The project supervisor submits the job order register to the account clerk for calculating the wages. Wages for workers are paid on the 25 th of each month by cash through cash withdrawal by the account clerk. To simplify the process, the account clerk records the monthly wages of these part-time workers on cash basis.",
      "options": [],
      "sourcePage": 1,
      "sourceMode": "text",
      "ocrUsed": false,
      "answer": "Module C (December 2019 Session) Page 13 of 13  validate if the management of Universe Limited discuss and challenge the key assumptions and estimates provided by Sky Limited for the cash flow projection;  meet with the management of Sky Limited to discuss and understand the key assumptions and estimates used in the cash flow forecast;  inquired with Sky Limited management if there are new rounds of financial funding obtained by Sky Limited after June 2018 that may be a good reference for estimating the latest fair value of Sky Limited;  perform an analytical review or audit procedures for the 2018 actual results of Sky Limited if feasible;  compare the 2018 actual results of Sky Limited to its budget to assess the reliability of management’s estimates;  compare the key assumptions and estimates used by the management with public available industry and market data. For example, compare the net profit margin percentage and discount rate applied with companies that engage in similar industry and of similar size;  as Universe Limited only holds 15% equity interest in Sky Limited, consider whether the management has applied appropriate minority shareholding discount in the valuation;  test the mathematical accuracy of the discounted cash flow calculation; and  test if the management of Universe Limited has applied the appropriate percentage of shareholding in calculating their share of the fair value of Sky Limited. * * * END OF EXAMINATION PAPER * * *",
